<subSubSection id="C36A657AFFE8FF9531CDFC4D3EE3FA62" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="8BCF36F1FFE8FF9531CDFC4D3BBDFB5E" blockId="24.[151,1437,1017,1438]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
<taxonomicName id="4C704D72FFE8FF9531CDFC4D3FA8FBED" authorityName="Zeller" authorityYear="1842" box="[151,238,1018,1041]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Sciapus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B904EAE3FFE8FF9531CDFC4D3FA8FBED" box="[151,238,1018,1041]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Sciapus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a quite restrictive distribution. Most 
<taxonomicName id="4C704D72FFE8FF953390FC4D3C67FBED" authorityName="Zeller" authorityYear="1842" box="[714,801,1018,1041]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Sciapus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B904EAE3FFE8FF953390FC4D3C67FBED" box="[714,801,1018,1041]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Sciapus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are primarily distributed in the Palearctic and Nearctic regions. As well, there is a record of 
<taxonomicName id="4C704D72FFE8FF95330AFBA93DE1FBC9" authorityName="Zeller" authorityYear="1842" box="[592,679,1054,1077]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Sciapus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B904EAE3FFE8FF95330AFBA93DE1FBC9" box="[592,679,1054,1077]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Sciapus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the Oriental realm, 
<taxonomicName id="4C704D72FFE8FF9532ECFBA93BB8FBCA" authority="Becker, 1922" authorityName="Becker" authorityYear="1922" box="[950,1278,1053,1078]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Sciapus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arctus">
<emphasis id="B904EAE3FFE8FF9532ECFBA93B1AFBC9" box="[950,1116,1054,1077]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Sciapus arctus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFE14B00FFE8FF95353DFBAA3BB8FBCA" author="Becker, T." box="[1127,1278,1053,1078]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" pagination="119 - 247" refId="ref24099" refString="Becker, T. (1922) Dipterologische Studien. Dolichopodidae der Indo-Australischen Region. Capita Zoologica, 1 (4), 119 - 247. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 132893" type="journal article" year="1922">Becker, 1922</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry id="F3677661FFE8FF953410FBAA3ADAFBCA" box="[1354,1436,1053,1078]" name="Taiwan" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Taiwan</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingCountry id="F3677661FFE8FF9531C5FBF63FAEFBA6" box="[159,232,1089,1114]" name="China" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">China</collectingCountry>
). As its 
<typeStatus id="54CB8853FFE8FF953017FBF63EE9FBA6" box="[333,431,1089,1114]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">holotype</typeStatus>
is lost, there is no way to track its detailed features. However Becker’s figure of the postabdomen (
<bibRefCitation id="EFE14B00FFE8FF953066FBD23D71FB82" author="Becker, T." box="[316,567,1125,1150]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" pagination="119 - 247" refId="ref24099" refString="Becker, T. (1922) Dipterologische Studien. Dolichopodidae der Indo-Australischen Region. Capita Zoologica, 1 (4), 119 - 247. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 132893" type="journal article" year="1922">Becker 1922, fig. 170</bibRefCitation>
) indicates it has a simple and digitiform cercus, which is similar to the new species we describe below. The new species is the only 
<taxonomicName id="4C704D72FFE8FF95325DFB3D3C18FB5D" authorityName="Zeller" authorityYear="1842" box="[775,862,1162,1185]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Sciapus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B904EAE3FFE8FF95325DFB3D3C18FB5D" box="[775,862,1162,1185]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Sciapus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
distributed in the Himalayan region.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCF36F1FFE8FF95319DFB1A3EE3FA62" blockId="24.[151,1437,1017,1438]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
Species of this genus can be distinguished by the following features: Head: vertex shallowly excavated, with strong postvertical bristles. Scape usually prolonged; arista-like stylus dorsal, nearly as long as head width. Thorax usually with dense pollinosity; with biseriate acr and 5–7 pairs of strong dc; with 2 pairs of sc, of which basal pair weak and hair-like. Legs: Hind femur with distinct anterior preapical bristle. Tarsi variously unornamented. Wing hyaline, crossvein dm-cu straight. Abdomen elongated, phallus and hypandrium arising from epandrial base, arching beyond epandrium, with distinct dorsal angle; epandrial lobe and surstylus often greatly elongated (
<bibRefCitation id="EFE14B00FFE8FF95340BFAD63F95FA62" author="Bickel, D. J." pageId="24" pageNumber="25" pagination="1 - 394" refId="ref24202" refString="Bickel, D. J. (1994) The Australian Sciapodinae (Diptera: Dolichopodidae), with a review of the Oriental and Australasian faunas, and a world conspectus of the subfamily. Records of the Australian Museum Supplement, 21, 1 - 394. https: // doi. org / 10.3853 / j. 0812 - 7387.21.1994.50" type="journal article" year="1994">Bickel 1994</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE14B00FFE8FF953187FA313EDFFA62" author="Yang, D. &amp; Zhang, L. &amp; Wang, M. &amp; Zhu, Y." box="[221,409,1413,1438]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" pagination="111 - 291" refId="ref25610" refString="Yang, D., Zhang, L., Wang, M. &amp; Zhu, Y. (2011) Fauna Sinica Insecta Uol. 53. Diptera Dolichopodidae. Science Press, Beijing, pp. 111 - 291." type="book chapter" year="2011">
Yang 
<emphasis id="B904EAE3FFE8FF953044FA313E16FA61" box="[286,336,1413,1437]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">et al</emphasis>
. 2011
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
